\description{
The main entry point for melliotab. Accepts data frames, model objects,
or correlation matrices and formats them according to the specified
citation style. Passing two or more model objects creates a side-by-side
model comparison table.
}
\section{Supported inputs}{

\code{melliotab()} is intended for table output inside R. It supports plain data
frames, matrices, base \code{table} objects, correlation matrices, common model
objects, hypothesis-test objects, and payloads created by \code{mellio_payload()}.
For objects that can produce several tables, call \code{melliotab(x)} once to
see the available \code{section} choices, then request one explicitly, for
example \code{melliotab(fit, section = "loadings")}.
}

\section{Common modifiers}{

The \verb{mt_*()} helpers are optional table modifiers. They follow the same
pattern as many R table packages: create a table once, then add formatting
only where needed. Common helpers include \code{mt_title()}, \code{mt_note()},
\code{mt_decimals()}, \code{mt_format_ci()}, \code{mt_remove_leading_zeros()},
\code{mt_sig_stars()}, \code{mt_spanner()}, \code{mt_indent()}, and
\code{mt_section_title()}.

Significance stars are never added by default. Use \code{mt_sig_stars()} only
when that convention is appropriate for your manuscript, course, or journal.
}

